<br>
I noticed most of you have been adding up the Evade and Armor Absorb factors like so.<br>
<br>
Merc:27%Absorb+5%Evade=31<br>
<br>
BM&amp;Zerker:19%Absorb+15%Evade=34<br>
<br>
Well, you can't think of it that way mainly because absorb factor just...absorbs possible damage.  Evade completely nulls the damage.  Think of it this way.<br>
<br>
BM/Zerk is hit with 100 damage 100 times.<br>
18% Absorb drops each attack to 81 damage.<br>
100x81=8100 damage.<br>
Then take evade into consideration.<br>
15% evade, on a very even(neither lucky nor unlucky)scale would null 15 attacks out of those 100.<br>
15x81=1215<br>
8100-1215=6885 total damage.<br>
<br>
Now for the merc.<br>
<br>
Merc is hit for 100 damage 100 times.<br>
27% Absorb bring each hit down to 73 damage.<br>
72x100=7300 damage<br>
Now evade<br>
Even scale nulls 5 attacks.<br>
5x73=365<br>
7300-365=6935 total damage.<br>
<br>
So on an even scale, a Blademaster or Berserker 50 less damage.  Now really, that's not too bad a difference.  <br>
<br>
Now let's try Merc with Evade II<br>
<br>
Merc is hit for 100 damage 100 times.<br>
27% Absorb bring each hit down to 73 damage.<br>
72x100=7300 damage<br>
Now evade<br>
Even scale nulls 10 attacks.<br>
10x73=730<br>
7300-730=6570 total damage.<br>
<br>
With Evade II a mercenary will take 315 less damage than the blademaster or berserker.<br>
<br>
&gt;.&gt;So, if we stay the same, a Blademaster or Berserker will take 50 less damage over a period of time.<br>
<br>
Change mercs and we take 315 less damage over a period of time than Blademaster or Berserker.  Nerf perhaps?  Or not.<br>
<br>
Now let's try 1000 atacks.<br>
<br>
BM/Zerker is hit 1000 time for 100 damage.<br>
19%Absorb brings each hit down to 81.<br>
1000x81=81000 total damage.<br>
15% Evade nulls 150 attacks on an even scale.<br>
150x81=12150<br>
81000-12150=68850 total damage.<br>
<br>
Merc is hit 1000 times for 100 damage.<br>
27%Absorb takes each hit down to 73.<br>
1000x73=73000 total damage.<br>
5%Evade on even scale nulls 50 attacks.<br>
50x73=3650<br>
73000-3650=69350 total damage.<br>
<br>
So being hit 1000 times for 100 damage, absorb and Evade factored in, a Blademaster or Berserker takes 500 less damage than a Mercenary.  Now that's a bit unbalanced...<br>
<br>
Now we'll try Evade II.<br>
<br>
Merc is hit 1000 times for 100 damage.<br>
27%Absorb takes each hit down to 73.<br>
1000x73=73000 total damage.<br>
10%Evade on even scale nulls 100 attacks.<br>
100x73=7300<br>
73000-7300=65700 total damage.<br>
<br>
Being hit 1000 time for 100 damage, Evade II will save a mercenary 3650 total damage.  Dayum...nerf, nerf, nerf...<br>
<br>
Now we'll try Evade 1.5(Your idea Demised)<br>
<br>
Merc is hit for 100 damage 100 times.<br>
27% Absorb bring each hit down to 73 damage.<br>
72x100=7300 damage<br>
7.5%Evade on even scale eliminates 7.5 attacks.<br>
7.5x73=547.5<br>
IMHO, the game rounds down when their secret formulae get a decimal, so...<br>
7300-547=6753 total damage.<br>
<br>
Even with only a slight boost of the theory of Evade 1.5, the mercenary will avoid 132 total damage.  &gt;.&gt;  Bit unbalanced, but let's try 1000 hits.<br>
<br>
Merc is hit 1000 times for 100 damage.<br>
27%Absorb takes each hit down to 73.<br>
1000x73=73000 total damage.<br>
7.5%Evade nulls 75 attacks on an even scale.<br>
75x73=5475.<br>
73000-5475=67525<br>
<br>
Even with the small boost of 2.5% more Evade, we will still avoid 1325 more damage than BM or Zerker.  Hrm...<br>
<br>
Then there's the idea of mercenaries giving up chain for Evade III.<br>
<br>
We are then driven into a roleplaying perspective.  Blademaster were given Reinforced because they need flexible material so they could be the lithe fighters they were.  Berserkers were given studded armor because it was flexible and was the closest thing to bear-hide clothing, of which many actual berserkers wore, that offered any protection.  Mercenaries were given chain mainly because the mercenary was usually depicted in books wearing chain.  Chain mail was much cheaper to purchase than an entire set of iron plate mail, was much lighter, did not require a squire to help equip one's self and did not make the undesirable noise of metal pans smashing together.<br>
<br>
So you see, this game is just as influenced by role-playing purposes than real facts.<br>
<br>
Well, that's the end of my arrogant foolishness.  Take into consideration that RA's and buffs were not worked into these calculations mainly because I'm a growing young adult and I'd prefer leaving my room at least once a day.<br>
<br>
