<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>From 1190 to 1350 knights wore a harness of mail; then, following the French defeat at Crecy, the stronger Plate Mail.  There was never any such thing as &quot;chain mail&quot;.  According to the OED, &quot;mail&quot; meant &quot;little spots,&quot; as derived from the Latin macula (as in the Immaculate Conception), in French mailles; but another word, malleus, meaning &quot;hammer,&quot; is a more likely derivation.  It was flexible and strong, so that we read of Richard I's crusaders in 1191 fighting unharmed with Saracen arrows sticking out of their mail like feathers.  It disappeared around 1650.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Also from this book,<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>A knight, fully armored, his leather undergarments smeared with grease, would be carrying a load of about sixty pounds, roughly the equivalent of a modern army backpack but distributed over his whole body.  Everything was carefully tailored: each knight would be measured and fitted by a master armorer, and if the knight could not be there in person he would send over wax models of his limbs.  The helmet would have heavy padding beneath the metal, though no armor could offer complete protection from a blow to the head or a direct strike by a mace.  The well equipped aristrocratic horseman was generally regarded as the single most powerful combatant on the battlefield; yet ventilation remained a potentially deadly problem.......An armored knight was like a tank, with almost no hearing and limited vision.  Hollywood films have depicted knights in armor needing the help of cranes to mount their horses, but the Metropolitan Museum in New York  has conducted trials with men in armor to show how a knight could run, leap in the air, lie down on his front or back and get up again without help, and climb onto and off of his horse (always a stallion).  It was exhausting but perfectly possible.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I haven't read far enough (if Chain Mail is at all in this book) to find where Chain Mail comes from.  But, as far as DAoC is concerned, the REALITY is, at those times, there was no such thing.<br>
<br>
As for Chain being easier to craft....you DO realize that it's made up of thousands of little &quot;rings&quot; or &quot;links&quot; that have to be &quot;weaved&quot; together and then the rings/links welded?  They have to be welded only to themselves, or else the mail isn't flexible.  The &quot;tighter&quot; the weave, the better the protection from pointy weapons, but the harder it is to make.<br>
<br>
Just saying,  I have to disagree...Plate Mail would be INFINITELY easier to make than Chain Mail.  Unless you're talking about crappy Chain Mail, that offers no where near the same protection as Plate.<br>
<br>
Armor crafting still exists today.  SCA and other organizations that re-enact that age, will get &quot;real&quot; armor made.  It would be interesting to get a quote from an armorcrafter to see if 2 plates (breast plate and backplate) fitted with leather straps to make them wearable, would cost nearly as much as a good quality &quot;tight weave&quot; suit of Chain Mail. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#ffffff><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub79.ezboard.com/blighttanksofdaoc.showUserPublicProfile?gid=xainder>Xainder</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 74<br> <font color=#000000>(6/21/03 10:10 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub79.ezboard.com/flighttanksofdaocfrm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=62.topic&index=37>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Armor &amp; History</span><hr size=1> From a person who is an actual 'smith' (Silversmith just so you know, but the processes and skills are all fudamentally the same for all metals) in real life, and someone who's personally making a real suit of Chainmail (If i ever get the damn thing done, since it does still take alot of time) for use at renasance festivals and historic recreation battles; i can assure you that Chainmail is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>much</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> cheaper and easier to produce, for many reasons. This is the reason why i'm making a suit of Chainmail, and plan to buy a 3rd-party produced Breastplate to finish out the suit. Since my forge is too small for me to make something so large.<br>
<br>
Firstly, you have to understand that it takes large amounts of heat to get a piece of metal upto working tempratures, since the entire piece of Platemail needs to be evenly heated for it to be smithed (read: Struck by <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>thousands-and-thousands-and-thousands</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of individual and precise blows to slowly form the raw material into the desired shape) and that heat takes a lot of time, effort, and cost to produce, especially in a low-tech enviroment. Chainmail has the luxury of being able to be made 'cold', needing only simple tools, and far less knowledge and skill to be crafted.<br>
<br>
Then, as you've stated, the armor needs to be <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>very</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> precisely fitted and formed, with many riveted interocking plates that need to slide and move perfectly together to achieve the range of motion needed to be able to preform in combat. Chainmail can have links added and rememoved as needed if the fit isn't good enough, also making it transferable from one persona to another, if need be. Unlike Platemail which would require so much reworking it's almost better just to have a new suit/piece made.<br>
<br>
The 'weave' and 'ring size' of Chainmail is also a big factor, with many different considerations coming into play when you think about the effort/cost of making a pice of it. A simple 2-on-2-on-2-on... construction, with large 1/2-inch rings, is actually <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>very</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> easy to get going, and progress can start to add up fast. But, such a weave is not nearly as tight (read: Offers much less protection, as the rings are more widly spaced, allowing for piercing weapons/arrows to slip past) as say a complex 6-8 ring weave done with 1/4-inch rings. More/smaller rings = more time = more cost. But that said, even a highly complex weave with small rings is still going be take far less work and skill to produce then the simplest of Platemail. Oh, and only the most costly of Chainmail will go as far as soldering each individual link into a solid ring, since yes, this inflates the cost/time. Even my modern suit i'm working on isn't soldered. Once the weave starts to take shape, it's actually quite amazing how strong it is, since each link gains strength by being a tiny part of the large whole.<br>
<br>
During it's day, Chainmail was considered the top-o-the-line 'poor mans' armor, with cured leather and quilted/padded cloth actually being the most common armor worn by the vast numbers of an army. And Platemail, with all its long-learned craftsmanship required to make, was reserved only for the most elite and/or royal of troops. The physical conditioning and training needed to use Platemail alone, reserved it for only select people. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#c0c0c0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub79.ezboard.com/blighttanksofdaoc.showUserPublicProfile?gid=demised>Demised</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Journeyman</span><br>  Posts: 16<br> <font color=#000000>(6/22/03 12:19 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub79.ezboard.com/flighttanksofdaocfrm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=62.topic&index=38>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.darkhosts.com/demised/trees5.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Armor &amp; History</span><hr size=1> Yeah, unless I'm mistaken, I believe those who wore platemail had to actually be 'trained' in order to be effective in it... <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.darkhosts.com/demised/chainwall.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#ffffff><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub79.ezboard.com/blighttanksofdaoc.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kerrecsnowmane>Kerrec Snowmane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Seasoned Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 111<br> <font color=#000000>(6/22/03 5:53 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub79.ezboard.com/flighttanksofdaocfrm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=62.topic&index=39>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Comparison</span><hr size=1> Hmm, maybe I'm (we're) looking at this wrong.<br>
<br>
You're saying it's easier and cheaper for the average Joe to make a suit of chain.  Are you assuming that all the links are premade?  He just buys them, gets some basic tools (pliers?) and off he goes?<br>
<br>
What about the time invested in making a link?  Making thousands of them?  The way I see it, a well equipped, experienced smith would have an easier time making a Breastplate than he would a Hauberk.  I see it as a matter of time, and in my book, time = $$$.  The making of the Hauberk may not be &quot;hard&quot;, but it's very time consuming. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#c0c0c0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub79.ezboard.com/blighttanksofdaoc.showUserPublicProfile?gid=theravensclaw>The Ravens Claw</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Journeyman</span><br>  Posts: 31<br> <font color=#000000>(6/22/03 10:27 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub79.ezboard.com/flighttanksofdaocfrm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=62.topic&index=40>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://avatars.cheetachat.com/img_ava/redmage.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Comparison</span><hr size=1> Well, not nescessarily.  As stated above, it all depends on the tightness of the weave.  Also stated above, a breastplate started out as a single sheet of iron.  The entire sheet would have to be heated to the point where all of it would have to be worked with.  Now think of it this way, imagine the effort and time it would take to heat roughly square yard of iron to working temperatures.  Then imagine the time it would take to pound that sheet into a carapace whilst still keeping the whole thing at working tempuratures so the metal would not be deformed.  Now chainmail.  You start out with yards and yards of wire and start clipping off 1/2 inch pieces.  Probably take you 30 minutes max to clip off all that if you were going at a moderate pace.  Then you start weaving the links together.  Going at a moderate pace it would probably take one about a week to make an entire chain skirt with sleeves.  An iron breastplate would maybe take three days or so.  But you can't think of it that way.  A smith would have to bash and heat up a piece of metal to cover every single inch of a man's body.  Ever notice in game how you buy a piece of chainmail for every part of your body?  Back in the day a suit of chainmail usually covered the entire torso, had sleeves and came down to the knees, skirt-like, and a mail coif.  Finish that off with leather gloves, leather pants and some hobnailed boots and you're fit for battle.  So the majority of the suit was just one piece.  I imagine an entire suit of platemail would take at least 3 weeks to make, while a suit of chainmail would take a week.<br>
<br>
That's beside's the point though.  Why are we arguing about what costs more where?  Can we get back on subject?  I love talking on these boards with you guys, but sometimes we should stay on subject of the topic.<br>
<br>
Oh, and the reason Minstrels get Chain and Evade II is they are on the rogue hitpoint table and don't have near the weaponskill we have.  We are on the Pure Melee hitpoint table and have a larger weaponskill.  Giving us Evade II and chain at the same time while having our large weaponskill would be overkill.<br>
